author: @ricardorien
text: Awesome class! This is what it looks like with types (don't judge me, looks cleaner for me after work for a while with TS): from typing import List, Optional class Manager(Employee):     def __init__(self, name: str, pay: int, employees: Optional[List[Employee]] = None):         super().__init__(name, pay)         if employees is None:             self.employees = []          else:             self.employees = employees       def add_emp(self, emp: Employee) -> None:         if emp not in self.employees:             self.employees.append(emp)      def remove_emp(self, emp: Employee) -> None:         if emp not in self.employees:             self.employees.remove(emp)      def print_emps(self) -> None:         for emp in self.employees:              print('-->', emp.fullname())

author: @Stardust314159
text: Do you use windows, and the "help" function bring up the following error?  'more' is not recognized as an internal or external command, operable program or batch file.  The help function needs to look in the System32 path in order to work. To make that happen: 1) Right-click the "My Computer" icon on your desktop and click "Properties". 2) On the "System" window brought up, click "Advanced System Settings" (should be on the left side if you're on Windows 7). 3) Click the "Advanced" tab, then the "Environment Variables..." button. 4) On the System Variables part (bottom for Windows 7), highlight the "PATH" variable and click the "Edit" button. 5) On the "Variable Value" input, add "C:\Windows\System32". Make sure the path is separated by the other paths by a semicolon. 6) DONE!

author: @user-xc5xf8gp8n
text: Corey talks about inheritance of classes in this video.   1. What is inheritence? It is a method that allows us to create a new class that shares the same attributes and method with the original function, and add some extra functionality to the new class. It also does not disturb the original class.   2. How to make a class inherit from another class? class Developer(Employee):   3. Structure of classes and subclasses. When we input a function to a subclass, python follows the 'method resolution order', which is the chain of classes that it goes through to find what the method is. All classes have the built-in group of methods and attributes as their primary order.   4. How to initiate the subclass so that it can handle more information than its original class can? There are 2 ways. first, using the super method as follows and pass in the arguments in interest. super.__init__()   Second, call the parent's init method explicitly and pass in the arguments in interest. Employee.init(self, first, last, )   5. Useful tools when exploring the inheritance system. .isinstance(instance, class) This method returns the boolean value of whether an instance belongs to a calss .issubclass(subclass, class) This method returns the boolean value of whether a class has inherited from the second class.   6. Example of class inheritance Whisky library   ++ when setting a default value for an ungiven argument, avoid using an empty mutable data type. That's a topic for another video.

author: @tonk6780
text: In case anybody ran into a Type Error using Python 2.7:  If you follow the video using Python 2.7, this line ... super().__init__(first, last, pay)  ... will give you this error: TypeError: super() takes at least 1 argument (0 given)  To fix this, you have to make a few cahnges to your code.  Declare your Employee function like this ...: class Employee(object):  ... and declare your subclass like so: class Developer(Employee):         raise_amount = 1.1         def __init__(self, first, last, pay, prog_lang):             super(Developer, self).__init__(first, last, pay)             self.prog_lang = prog_lang  The subclass has to be declared as a *"new-style"* class so that the super() will work. Python 2 seems to create old style classes unless instructed otherwise. In Python 3 you won't have to deal with this problem, because it apparently always creates new style classes.  More information here: https://stackoverflow.com/a/1713052

Hi Corey, Thanks again for the video. I am using Python2.7 . When i try to print all employees, it prints "None" also. Please advise. Also as someone mentioned in the comments i had to use "parentclass.__init__" instead of super to get this working.  This is the script:: Tue Feb 14 20:23:32 root@ansible:/var/tmp/python283 cat class9.py #!/usr/bin/python import string,datetime  class employee:         no_of_emps = 0         bonus_percent = 1.04         def __init__(self,first,last,pay):                 self.first = string.lower(first)                 self.last  = string.lower(last)                 self.pay   = pay                 self.email = self.first + '.' + self.last + '@gmail.com'                 employee.no_of_emps += 1          def fullname(self):                 return '{} {}'.format(self.first, self.last)           def pay(self):                 return '{}'.format(self.pay)           def email(self):                 return '{}'.format(self.email)          def bonus(self):                 return '{}'.format(int(self.pay * self.bonus_percent))  class developer(employee):         bonus_percent = 1.10          def __init__(self,first,last,pay,prog_lang):                 employee.__init__(self,first,last,pay)                 self.prog_lang = prog_lang  class manager(employee):         bonus_percent = 1.20          def __init__(self,first,last,pay,emps='None'):                 employee.__init__(self,first,last,pay)                 if emps is None:                         self.emps = []                 else:                         self.emps = emps          def add_emp(self,emp):                 if emp not in self.emps:                         self.emps.append(emp)          def remove_emp(self,emp):                 if emp in self.emps:                         self.emps.remove(emp)          def print_all_emps(self):                 for emp in self.emps:                         print "-->", emp.fullname()   dev1 = developer('John', 'Doe', 30000, 'Python') dev2 = developer('David', 'Miller', 40000, 'Java')  mgr1 = manager('Mike','Lu',30000,[dev1])  print "MANAGER EMAIL ID:", mgr1.email print "ALL EMPLOYES WORKING FOR HIM
", mgr1.print_all_emps() mgr1.add_emp(dev2) print "ALL EMPLOYES WORKING FOR HIM AFTER ADDING 2nd Developer
", mgr1.print_all_emps() mgr1.remove_emp(dev1) print "ALL EMPLOYES WORKING FOR HIM AFTER REMOVING 1st Developer
", mgr1.print_all_emps()  Tue Feb 14 20:23:35 root@ansible:/var/tmp/python284    This is the output:: Tue Feb 14 20:23:35 root@ansible:/var/tmp/python284 python class9.py MANAGER EMAIL ID: mike.lu@gmail.com ALL EMPLOYES WORKING FOR HIM --> john doe None ALL EMPLOYES WORKING FOR HIM AFTER ADDING 2nd Developer --> john doe --> david miller None ALL EMPLOYES WORKING FOR HIM AFTER REMOVING 1st Developer --> david miller None Tue Feb 14 20:23:43 root@ansible:/var/tmp/python285
